00:16:24.320 --> 00:16:27.260
competition which is on the growing side,
okay?

00:16:27.260 --> 00:16:31.680
And this is actually in Brazil. So what they
do there is -- these are farmers. They

00:16:31.680 --> 00:16:34.310
submit samples of their coffee and there's
a

00:16:34.310 --> 00:16:38.370
jury that comes and judges these coffees,
gives

00:16:38.370 --> 00:16:43.000
them scores. There's a national jury. So for
example, in Brazil, there were 250 farmers

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:48.040
who
entered. The national jury narrowed it down

00:16:48.040 --> 00:16:52.170
to
50 samples. And then came the international

00:16:52.170 --> 00:17:00.160
jury. Okay? So I schmoozled my way on to the
international jury in Brazil last year. And

00:17:00.160 --> 00:17:02.960
what you do here is, you get eight coffees
--

00:17:02.960 --> 00:17:10.459
eight or ten coffees every round -- and you
start by -- let's see, well, that's me doing

00:17:10.459 --> 00:17:12.891
my
thing. But you start by smelling. There's

00:17:12.891 --> 00:17:15.120
a
lot of smelling going on. So you start by

00:17:15.120 --> 00:17:21.120
smelling it when it's just ground. It's very
interesting. Then you pour water into it and

00:17:21.120 --> 00:17:23.630
you wait four minutes and you start smelling
it

00:17:23.630 --> 00:17:29.360
again. You remove the crema from the top at
which point the aroma starts exploding in

00:17:29.360 --> 00:17:32.409
a very, very nice way. And
then, you go start tasting. You go around

00:17:32.409 --> 00:17:34.799
the
tables and you taste and you taste for about

00:17:34.799 --> 00:17:37.039
45
minutes. And the coffees actually change their

00:17:37.039 --> 00:17:42.850
tastes during this time. Some of them lose
their structure. I learned this term from

00:17:42.850 --> 00:17:46.720
listening to the coffee people. And then,
after these 45 minutes, you fill out a form

00:17:46.720 --> 00:17:49.250
and
you give a score. You go into another room

00:17:49.250 --> 00:17:52.249
and you have a discussion.
It's just like a program committee discussion

00:17:52.249 --> 00:17:56.080
in a conference. And people start throwing
all

00:17:56.080 --> 00:18:02.250
kinds of words. The flavors of the coffee.
They throw out all kinds of flavors. That

00:18:02.250 --> 00:18:05.620
was
coffee. That was not, you know, what you guys

00:18:05.620 --> 00:18:10.380
just said. And then, they start talking about
the acidity. The acidity is really the spirit

00:18:10.380 --> 00:18:17.110
of the coffee. The acidity can come in all
kinds of ways. And then you go back and you

00:18:17.110 --> 00:18:18.700
do
another eight coffees and another eight coffees

00:18:18.700 --> 00:18:26.220
and you do this all day. It's kind of fun
actually. You slurp. It's just like wine.

00:18:26.220 --> 00:18:34.600
You spit most of it out. And this is the
deliberations of the jury. And then at the

00:18:34.600 --> 00:18:37.470
end
of the week, we went through round one, two,

00:18:37.470 --> 00:18:43.970
and three. We gave an award to this very lucky
person. The interesting thing about this is

00:18:43.970 --> 00:18:50.070
that the coffees that get the Cup of Excellence
stamp on them, they participate in an Internet

00:18:50.070 --> 00:18:55.360
auction. So roasters from all around the world
can bid for these things. So this guy, for

00:18:55.360 --> 00:19:02.950
example, sold his lot for something like 25
dollars a pound. Compare this to three that

00:19:02.950 --> 00:19:06.770
you would get on the market for -- that's
the

00:19:06.770 --> 00:19:08.960
running price, okay? So these guys really
--

00:19:08.960 --> 00:19:11.480
now, he's not selling his whole, you know,
crop

00:19:11.480 --> 00:19:18.850
for this, but again, it's more the glory -- I
mean, this guy is one out of 350,000 farmers

00:19:18.850 --> 00:19:23.370
in
Brazil; he's the "Cup of Excellence". It helps

00:19:23.370 --> 00:19:26.249
the -- that's the other
interesting thing here -- it creates direct

00:19:26.249 --> 00:19:30.460
relationships between farmers and roasters
and

00:19:30.460 --> 00:19:32.500
importers. So before this what happened is
all

00:19:32.500 --> 00:19:37.879
the farmers in Brazil take their coffees and
they put it into four big bins. And what you

00:19:37.879 --> 00:19:42.710
get is, you get four choices of coffees from
Brazil. Where in any country that grows coffee,

00:19:42.710 --> 00:19:48.130
you get hundreds of
really interesting different flavors of coffee.

00:19:48.130 --> 00:19:53.649
So now, they can work directly with the
roasters. The roasters can come invest in

00:19:53.649 --> 00:19:56.749
a
particular farm, work with them multiple years

00:19:56.749 --> 00:20:00.779
and really create a relationship. And that
completely changes the dynamics of the

00:20:00.779 --> 00:20:06.440
coffee world. And this happened in the last
ten years. We always think as tech people

00:20:06.440 --> 00:20:10.570
we're advancing the world at a speed no one
can

00:20:10.570 --> 00:20:12.260
catch up. But the changes in coffee world
in the

00:20:12.260 --> 00:20:20.349
last 15 years have been mind boggling. I
went -- this is in Costa Rica. So this is

00:20:20.349 --> 00:20:24.070
--
this is how coffee comes, okay?This is where

00:20:24.070 --> 00:20:29.399
coffee comes from. These cherries which you
can actually chew on. And in fact, people

00:20:29.399 --> 00:20:31.090
for
many years only chewed on them before they

00:20:31.090 --> 00:20:33.779
realized there's something good in here we
can

00:20:33.779 --> 00:20:38.571
roast and put in our lattes. This is what
they

00:20:38.571 --> 00:20:42.769
come from. So it's a very colorful activity
if

00:20:42.769 --> 00:20:50.840
you like. So I tried to cover -- I tried to
follow coffee history a little bit. I went

00:20:50.840 --> 00:20:54.360
to
Ethiopia. So those of you who know Yirgacheffe

00:20:54.360 --> 00:21:00.179
is a region that's known for its very wonderful
coffees. You can see Yirgacheffe. I went to

00:21:00.179 --> 00:21:08.350
the Yirgacheffe. This is a really interesting
experience. After the -- from Ethiopia, coffee

00:21:08.350 --> 00:21:11.419
moved on to the Arabian peninsula, to the
Ottoman

00:21:11.419 --> 00:21:18.100
Empire. I tried to go to the Ottoman Empire.
Turns out it's too late. [laughter] But I

00:21:18.100 --> 00:21:23.029
went pretty
close. This is the old city in Jerusalem where

00:21:23.029 --> 00:21:27.590
you go there and you think
you're in the Ottoman Empire. Actually, it's

00:21:27.590 --> 00:21:30.919
kind of interesting. The story of how coffee
came

00:21:30.919 --> 00:21:41.710
into the world is kind of vague. So the legend
that everybody knows about is how the goat

00:21:41.710 --> 00:21:47.420
herder who saw his goats prancing and he said,
"Oh, why are they dancing?They were eating

00:21:47.420 --> 00:21:52.649
some red cherries. And he said I'll have some
of that. [laughter] Actually about he said

00:21:52.649 --> 00:21:56.350
let me wait a
day. See what happens to my goats. If they're

00:21:56.350 --> 00:22:00.320
still alive tomorrow, I'll also have some
of

00:22:00.320 --> 00:22:04.070
that. [laughter] But actually, what turns
out is what is

00:22:04.070 --> 00:22:10.970
the leading theory today is that discovering
coffee was actually due to the Chinese, which

00:22:10.970 --> 00:22:15.899
is kind of not what you would expect. What
happened was in the 15th century, there were

00:22:15.899 --> 00:22:18.559
a
bunch of fleet -- very big ships that came

00:22:18.559 --> 00:22:22.460
from
China to Yemen. They were looking for all

00:22:22.460 --> 00:22:26.809
kinds of great things from Africa. They were
bringing giraffes back for the emperor and

00:22:26.809 --> 00:22:31.259
stuff like that. There
were 200 ship fleets. And they came to Yemen

00:22:31.259 --> 00:22:32.429
and
they brought their tea with them. And the

00:22:32.429 --> 00:22:36.580
Arabs saw that you can actually put a leaf
in

00:22:36.580 --> 00:22:43.179
hot water and get something good out of it.
And very abruptly , the Chinese stopped

00:22:43.179 --> 00:22:47.440
sending -- they decided one day to stop this
fleet. And the Arabs were like, "hey, where

00:22:47.440 --> 00:22:49.760
is
our tea? We need this tea. " So they started

00:22:49.760 --> 00:22:54.210
looking around,
"where are we going to find some tea?" So

00:22:54.210 --> 00:22:55.519
they
walked over -- not walked over -- they went

00:22:55.519 --> 00:23:01.080
over -- in the Red Sea there's a very narrow
passage from Yemen to Ethiopia. And they

00:23:01.080 --> 00:23:07.710
started looking around and they found the
leaves of the coffee tree in Ethiopia. After

00:23:07.710 --> 00:23:11.519
awhile, they realized there was something
actually better than the leaves. There was

00:23:11.519 --> 00:23:14.299
the bean and you could roast it but that took
another hundred years.

00:23:14.299 --> 00:23:22.350
So that's the leading theory how coffee
became something that we drink today. In Ethiopia,

00:23:22.350 --> 00:23:28.610
3,000 years ago, people were chewing the bean.
They were making golf ball sized snacks out

00:23:28.610 --> 00:23:33.500
of it
before they went out to war. That is how they

00:23:33.500 --> 00:23:37.690
consumed coffee. So, I also, you know, in
my

00:23:37.690 --> 00:23:47.220
dedication to the project, I paid a lot of
money for coffee. So until 2009, my 7 dollars

00:23:47.220 --> 00:23:51.481
