00:34:53.760 --> 00:35:00.000
In
fact, I did it in Costa Rica after that.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:02.599
United States of America, okay. So this is
one

00:35:02.599 --> 00:35:07.970
of the -- I have a section in the book about
the United States. It's a sad story for the

00:35:07.970 --> 00:35:12.521
first 200 years. Fortunately, due to Alfred
Peet

00:35:12.521 --> 00:35:21.250
. This is his first store in Berkeley. He
turned things around; he showed people that

00:35:21.250 --> 00:35:28.900
coffee is actually an art and should not be
judged by the level of the commercial on TV.

00:35:28.900 --> 00:35:34.500
And basically all the great coffee we know
about today is the inspiration of Alfred Peet.

00:35:34.500 --> 00:35:39.450
That's not to say the roast -- Alfred Pete
actually had a relatively dark roast and he

00:35:39.450 --> 00:35:42.089
actually
trained the Starbucks guys how to roast and

00:35:42.089 --> 00:35:45.970
brew coffee.
But the idea that there is so much going into

00:35:45.970 --> 00:35:49.630
coffee came from Alfred Peet
and then a whole bunch of other people made

00:35:49.630 --> 00:35:53.829
it into
what it is today. So today you can go to

00:35:53.829 --> 00:35:59.270
places like Four Barrel or hang out at Google
and have Four Barrel coffee and you're really

00:35:59.270 --> 00:36:06.190
getting some of the best coffee in the world.
How did I approach the coffee world? I didn't

00:36:06.190 --> 00:36:07.819
know
anybody in the coffee world. When I started

00:36:07.819 --> 00:36:10.319
I
had to get my way in. Of course there's the

00:36:10.319 --> 00:36:13.690
infinite charm of a database expert trying
to

00:36:13.690 --> 00:36:15.811
help you with your data needs, right? [laughter]
So I

00:36:15.811 --> 00:36:21.670
approached people with fusion tables and saying
"hey, I can map your data and show you all

00:36:21.670 --> 00:36:23.890
kinds
of things." Sometimes that worked. But when

00:36:23.890 --> 00:36:27.160
that didn't work, there's always schwag. I
traveled

00:36:27.160 --> 00:36:31.970
around the world giving people various Google
schwag

00:36:31.970 --> 00:36:37.339
items; that really opened any door I wanted.
This is my host in Bosnia. I gave her more

00:36:37.339 --> 00:36:45.430
than a hat. But she was so happy. And then,
she had a birthday a little later that her

00:36:45.430 --> 00:36:47.961
mom
made her a Google cake with a Google hat and

00:36:47.961 --> 00:36:56.329
you can see happiness. [laughter] So if you
see -- so there are a lot of coffee people

00:36:56.329 --> 00:37:00.590
going around meeting at highfalutin coffee
conferences comparing their Google schwag

00:37:00.590 --> 00:37:01.590
now. And
that --

00:37:01.590 --> 00:37:02.800
&gt;&gt;Male #12: That's your fault.

