fine-ground. So that's -- and you know, my
family had.

00:47:56.750 --> 00:47:57.750
[laughter]

00:47:57.750 --> 00:48:05.500
&gt;&gt; Alon: There is a particular flavor called
Rio which is -- and it's something that for

00:48:05.500 --> 00:48:08.619
example in the Arab countries is actually
very

00:48:08.619 --> 00:48:14.460
prized in coffee. But you know in the cupping
competition if you would identify Rio in the

00:48:14.460 --> 00:48:21.900
cup, it would be eliminated. So a lot of these
things are subjective. But Brazil is such

00:48:21.900 --> 00:48:24.750
a
huge country and the farms are so large. I

00:48:24.750 --> 00:48:29.599
mean, we went to a farm that produced more
coffee than the entire country of Bolivia,

00:48:29.599 --> 00:48:36.150
which is substantial. And it's grown in
relatively low altitudes compared to a lot

00:48:36.150 --> 00:48:40.260
of
the other places. So the flavors tend to be

00:48:40.260 --> 00:48:45.720
sweeter, more chocolatety, caramelly things.
And so, it provides a good base for a lot

00:48:45.720 --> 00:48:51.730
of espresso.
You'll see a lot of espressos with a lot of

00:48:51.730 --> 00:48:59.049
Brazil in them with a few other things.

00:48:59.049 --> 00:49:00.306
&gt;&gt; Louis: The taste for roasting, it's lighter
roast.

00:49:00.306 --> 00:49:01.306
&gt;&gt; Alon: Yeah.

00:49:01.306 --> 00:49:02.306
&gt;&gt; Louis: Do coffee growers generally like
coffee?

00:49:02.306 --> 00:49:08.839
&gt;&gt; Alon: That's changing. So if you go to
what I would call the leading coffee growers,

00:49:08.839 --> 00:49:15.670
they're actually learning cupping and learning
barista activities and -- it's actually really

00:49:15.670 --> 00:49:20.970
interesting to see. When I went to Central
America, you know the coffee grower that I

00:49:20.970 --> 00:49:24.480
was
visiting -- Aida Batlle-- she's a fifth generation

00:49:24.480 --> 00:49:27.470
coffee
grower. She just got this highfalutin espresso

00:49:27.470 --> 00:49:33.380
machine. And she got a certificate from the
Barista Association of America that she's

00:49:33.380 --> 00:49:36.059
a
certified barista. It's actually really interesting

00:49:36.059 --> 00:49:40.369
to see the
producers and the baristas are coming together.

00:49:40.369 --> 00:49:45.969
In fact, this year was the first time a barista
from the producing country won the

00:49:45.969 --> 00:49:52.329
championship from El Salvador. It was mind-boggling
presentation.[inaudible]

00:49:52.329 --> 00:49:59.400
[laughter]
But you can go see it on the web. It's really

00:49:59.400 --> 00:50:02.140
-- these
people do amazing things. This guy for

00:50:02.140 --> 00:50:09.369
example, he had his coffee roasted in England,
all right? By some highfalutin roaster. And

00:50:09.369 --> 00:50:12.589
he wanted to figure out how many days since
the

00:50:12.589 --> 00:50:15.730
roast date would be the best date to serve
the

00:50:15.730 --> 00:50:17.869
coffee. And furthermore, the competition was
in

00:50:17.869 --> 00:50:20.660
Bogotá, Columbia, which is a high altitude
that

00:50:20.660 --> 00:50:26.519
changes the way the creme acts and so on.
So what he did was, he took a

00:50:26.519 --> 00:50:30.830
bunch of coffees that he got from the roaster
and he went up to a high

00:50:30.830 --> 00:50:35.480
mountain in El Salvador and he basically
prepared the coffee every day until he figured

00:50:35.480 --> 00:50:38.230
out
that two weeks from the day of roasting was

00:50:38.230 --> 00:50:40.640
the
right time for this particular bean. And so,

00:50:40.640 --> 00:50:42.190
he went to Colombia and he extended all this
and he won the

00:50:42.190 --> 00:50:43.190
championship.

00:50:43.190 --> 00:50:44.190
[laughter].

00:50:44.190 --> 00:50:46.989
&gt;&gt; Alon: Just amazing..

00:50:46.989 --> 00:50:52.189
&gt;&gt; Louis: How do you like to roast your
coffee?

00:50:52.189 --> 00:50:55.120
&gt;&gt; Alon: I'm waiting for your recipe, man.
I

00:50:55.120 --> 00:51:01.160
like it light. But it's actually harder to
roast light.

00:51:01.160 --> 00:51:05.450
&gt;&gt; Louis: It is.
&gt;&gt;Alon: It's more brittle. So I'm waiting

00:51:05.450 --> 00:51:06.869
for the -- we have -- Louis and I have the
same

00:51:06.869 --> 00:51:12.730
roasting machine. So I've gone through -- you
know, I bought an espresso machine. I bought

00:51:12.730 --> 00:51:16.190
a
roaster. Almost the entire chain of coffee

00:51:16.190 --> 00:51:21.640
production is in my home except I don't grow
the coffee. Hector, a few years ago, bought

00:51:21.640 --> 00:51:26.900
us a
coffee plant. On the Internet. It was

00:51:26.900 --> 00:51:30.579
blossoming doing very well. It takes about
three or four years until it starts producing

00:51:30.579 --> 00:51:33.011
fruit, but
then he went to Colombia for two weeks before

00:51:33.011 --> 00:51:42.390
Christmas and it died. The water we gave it
was not the right water.

00:51:42.390 --> 00:51:47.920
&gt;&gt;Louis: I have one final question. If you
have to pick between the place that has

00:51:47.920 --> 00:51:54.130
mediocre coffee but good atmosphere and culture
the other way around great coffee but some

00:51:54.130 --> 00:51:55.519
nasty place?

00:51:55.519 --> 00:52:02.339
&gt;&gt; Alon: So the great coffee is not in any
nasty places. I enjoy Oslo. I enjoy, London

00:52:02.339 --> 00:52:05.710
actually
has great cafes. Melbourne is not a nasty

00:52:05.710 --> 00:52:10.660
place. Personally, I would say c'est la vie
-- that's

00:52:10.660 --> 00:52:16.119
obviously because of particular. I would
not -- I don't think I could survive in Paris

00:52:16.119 --> 00:52:23.300
anymore. There are a few good cafes emerging.
Once you start getting into the coffee world,

00:52:23.300 --> 00:52:26.500
actually your life becomes harder, because
you

00:52:26.500 --> 00:52:34.190
can't just walk into any cafe and have coffee.
It's -- and that's why the aeropress is getting

00:52:34.190 --> 00:52:38.769
popular. Because people who care about their
coffee, they bring their hand grinders, their

00:52:38.769 --> 00:52:42.209
own beans, their aeropress. That's how they
survive trips.

00:52:42.209 --> 00:52:48.339
&gt;&gt; Male #24: So the coffee culture besides
complementary environment culture is complementary

00:52:48.339 --> 00:52:53.619
culture of bakery.
La brioche, or croissant which are very different

00:52:53.619 --> 00:52:56.769
from different
countries. From your experience which one

00:52:56.769 --> 00:52:59.559
is
the most interesting, most different.

00:52:59.559 --> 00:53:01.130
&gt;&gt; Alon: So where?

00:53:01.130 --> 00:53:04.020
&gt;&gt;Male #24: Like cultures, bakery for coffee.

00:53:04.020 --> 00:53:10.170
&gt;&gt; Alon: So a lot of times good bakery
culture is, you know, makes up for bad coffee.

00:53:10.170 --> 00:53:17.809
So that's why Paris exists. That's in Vienna
you can go to places where, you know, the

00:53:17.809 --> 00:53:21.910
coffee is not great, but the pastries are
really good. I found, for example, Melbourne

00:53:21.910 --> 00:53:29.010
have really nice food in cafes. There's
certain places where you really find some

00:53:29.010 --> 00:53:33.940
reasonable food.
You can sit there for longer. London -- again,

00:53:33.940 --> 00:53:37.310
the all the nice cafes in London are Australians
and

00:53:37.310 --> 00:53:44.369
Kiwis who moved to London to open cafes and
teach the Brits what to do. But then, like

00:53:44.369 --> 00:53:51.220
in
the U.S., the great cafes don't actually have

00:53:51.220 --> 00:54:00.099
food. They might have a scone.

00:54:00.099 --> 00:54:03.640
&gt;&gt; Louis: You're the envy of every Googler.

00:54:03.640 --> 00:54:04.640
[laughter].

00:54:04.640 --> 00:54:05.640
&gt;&gt; Alon: Thank you very much.

00:54:05.640 --> 00:54:05.641
[Applause]

